nt":188,"object_id":997889,"filter":"raw"},"18996":{"term_id":18996,"name":"Wal-Mart","slug":"wal-mart","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":59633,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":82,"object_id":997889,"filter":"raw"},"6634954":{"term_id":6634954,"name":"Wal-Mart Stores","slug":"wal-mart-stores","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":59634,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":26,"object_id":997889,"filter":"raw"},"15387":{"term_id":15387,"name":"Walmart","slug":"walmart","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":59646,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":51,"object_id":997889,"filter":"raw"}},"has_commentary_tag":false,"primary_tag":{"name":"Walmart","slug":"walmart","url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/tag\/walmart\/"},"paid":false,"paid_excerpt":"Wal-Mart reported decent holiday quarter results but its forecasts suggest it knows it has to raise its game a few notches.","seo":{"seo_title":"Wal-Mart had a good holiday season. But forecasts show lots yet to do.","seo_description":"The discount juggernaut has to raise its game a few notches.","seo_keywords":"","seo_news_keywords":"","seo_additional_meta":""},"social":{"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ffortune.com%2F2015%2F02%2F19%2Fwalmarts-holiday-results%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Ffor.tn%2F1LeStSM","encoded_title":"Ok%2C+so+Walmart%E2%80%99s+US+sales+improved.+But+tons+of+challenges%C2%A0remain","twitter_text":"Wal-Mart's plans to fix its business will cost it $WMT","twitter_via":"FORTUNE","facebook_desc":"The discount juggernaut has to raise its game a few notches.","facebook_title":"Wal-Mart had a good holiday season. But forecasts show lots yet to do."},"format":{"term_id":2710,"name":"Article","slug":"fortune-post-format-article","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":3,"taxonomy":"fortune_post_format","description":"","parent":0,"count":11115,"filter":"raw"},"related_posts":[],"in_article_ad_id":["in-article-ad-997889-0","in-article-ad-997889-1"]},{"id":997895,"content_type":"free full","is_magazine_content":"non-magazine","url":"\/2015\/02\/19\/when-mentors-cross-the-line\/","title":"When mentors cross the line","content":"<p><em>The New York Times Magazine<\/em> <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nytimes.com\/2015\/02\/15\/magazine\/the-stanford-undergraduate-and-the-mentor.html\" target=\"_blank\">recently profiled<\/a> the troubling, potentially criminal relationship between a former Stanford student, Ellie Clougherty, and entrepreneur Joe Lonsdale who was, among other things, Clougherty\u2019s mentor for the undergraduate course Engineering 145: Technology Entrepreneurship.<\/p>\n<p>As the story unfolds, it becomes increasingly disturbing. Lonsdale and Clougherty\u2019s relationship evolves from that of a mentor and mentee into a romantic relationship and then, Clougherty alleges, into something much more disturbing\u2014including sexual harassment and assault. Clougherty took the case to Stanford officials and Lonsdale was banned from the Stanford campus for ten years (though that ban seems theoretical at best, given that, according to Bazelon, \u201cLonsdale has been invited to campus for a private lunch which he attended with the university\u2019s permission.\u201d). Clougherty filed a civil suit in January and Lonsdale has <a href=\"http:\/\/joelonsdalestatement.com\/\">responded, vigorously<\/a>, and filed a countersuit, denying Clougherty\u2019s accusations.<\/p>\n<p>Clougherty graduated from Stanford in 2013 and is looking to build a career that involves brain research, tech and social activism.<\/p>\n<p>It\u2019s a murky situation\u2014but a mentoring relationship went horribly wrong. Clearly both professional and personal boundaries were crossed inappropriately\u2014and a young woman who was supposed to be mentored and encouraged professionally was, instead, embroiled in what was, at <em>best<\/em>, an unhealthy relationship with someone who possessed undue influence.<\/p>\n<p>There is ample evidence that mentoring for college students can have a significant impact on how prepared recent graduates feel as they enter the workplace. A <a href=\"https:\/\/www.insidehighered.com\/news\/2014\/05\/06\/gallup-surveys-graduates-gauge-whether-and-why-college-good-well-being\">2014 Gallup study<\/a> of 30,000 college students found that mentoring opportunities were remarkably important to long term career success and satisfaction. Brandon Busteed, the executive director of Gallup Education <a href=\"https:\/\/www.insidehighered.com\/views\/2014\/09\/25\/essay-about-importance-mentors-college-students\">noted<\/a> how the study revealed that, \u201cthe three most potent elements linked to long-term success for college grads relate to emotional support: feeling that they had a professor who made them excited about learning, that the professors at their alma mater cared about them as a person, and that they had a mentor who encouraged them to pursue their goals and dreams.\u201d<\/p>\n<p>Lonsdale never treated Clougherty as someone who had goals and dreams. Instead, Lonsdale, by engaging in a personal relationship with his young mentee, treated her as a romantic conquest. He ignored his professional responsibility for personal gain. Lonsdale insists that, \u201cEllie is a forceful person,\u201d as if, somehow, that negates the inherent power imbalance not only in a mentor\/mentee relationship, but also between a 21-year old college student and a hugely successful 29-year old entrepreneur.<\/p>\n<p>It should go without saying, but mentors cannot treat the mentor\/mentee relationship as a garden of earthly delights. They have one primary responsibility in such a relationship\u2014to provide support and guidance for young men and women. Mentees are not potential romantic interests or sexual conquests. They are not potential acolytes or personal assistants. The mentor\/mentee relationship is a professional one and should be treated as such. If there is a temptation to cross lines, resist. There is a responsibility attached to being a mentor. Mentors must live up to that responsibility. It really is that simple.<\/p>\n<p>Alumni are a natural source of mentoring for colleges and universities. These alumni and their success stories are living proof that the education at any given college or university works, and that the current students are making a wise, invaluable investment in their future. Joe Lonsdale is one of countless alumni who have been tapped by their alma maters to work with promising undergraduates. Unfortunately, though, many universities seem to think that getting mentors on campus is all they need to do. There is, all too often, little oversight and few systems in place to help students when these relationships become troubled.<\/p>\n<p>Universities and colleges can\u2019t merely provide mentoring opportunities for their students. They need to monitor those relationships to ensure they are functioning productively and mutually for both the mentor and the mentee. There needs to be a system of checks and balances, if you will. Had the professor of the course who originally assigned Lonsdale to mentor Ellie Clougherty engaged in even the most basic of oversight, a great deal of suffering might have been averted. We cannot undo what has been done but universities and colleges can work to ensure that such a problematic mentoring relationship never happens again.<\/p>\n<p><em>Roxane Gay is an English professor at Purdue University and a <\/em>New York Times<em> best-selling author. She\u2019s written <\/em>Ayiti, An Untamed State, Bad Feminist,<em> and the forthcoming<\/em>Hunger<em>. She is also editor of <\/em><a href=\"http:\/\/the-toast.net\/category\/the_butter\/\" target=\"_blank\">The Butter<\/a>. <em>Roxane\u2019s column for <\/em>Fortune<em>, <a href=\"http:\/\/fortune.com\/tag\/beyond-the-workplace\/\" target=\"_blank\">\u201cBeyond the Workplace,\u201d<\/a> will delve into why corporate America should care about the social issues happening outside of the office. Follow her at <a href=\"http:\/\/twitter.com\/rgay\" target=\"_blank\">@rgay<\/a>.<\/em><\/p>\n","time":{"pretty":"February 19, 2015","published":"2015-02-19 11:39:47","updated":"2015-02-19 11:39:47","minute":"11:39 AM EST","is_same_day":true,"is_home_pop":true},"comment_url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/19\/when-mentors-cross-the-line\/","absolute_url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/19\/when-mentors-cross-the-line\/","redirect_url":"","partner":"","outbrain_url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/19\/when-mentors-cross-the-line\/","outbrain_footer":true,"outbrain_right_rail":true,"short_title":"When mentors cross the line","post_type":"post","featured_type":"image","featured_image":{"src":"https:\/\/fortunedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/01\/20140131-_gay_0026.jpg?quality=80&w=407","class":"featured-img-article_portrait","credit":"Jay Grabiec","caption":"Author Roxane Gay","attach_id":"955268"},"excerpt":"The mentor\/mentee relationship is a professional one and should be treated as such. It really is that simple.","authors":[{"id":"955252","url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/author\/roxane-gay\/","name":"Roxane Gay","twitter":"rgay","gplus":"","email":"","thumbnail":"<img width=\"39\" height=\"59\" src=\"https:\/\/fortunedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/01\/20140131-_gay_0026.jpg?quality=80&amp;w=39\" class=\"avatar avatar-59 photo wp-post-image\" alt=\"Roxane Gay\" \/>","thumbnail_alt":"Roxane Gay","thumbnail_src":["https:\/\/fortunedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/01\/20140131-_gay_0026.jpg?quality=80&w=100",100,150,true],"bio":"Roxane Gay is an English professor at Purdue University and a New York Times best-selling author. She's written Ayiti, An Untamed State, Bad Feminist, and the forthcoming Hunger. ","title":"","company":"","is_contributor":"not-contributor"}],"sections":[{"term_id":911967,"name":"MPW","slug":"mpw","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":116938,"taxonomy":"category","description":"Fortune's coverage of the Most Powerful Women in business.","parent":0,"count":971,"filter":"raw"}],"section":{"name":"MPW","slug":"mpw","url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/mpw\/","newsletter_info":"The Broadsheet"},"tags":[{"term_id":232778154,"name":"Beyond the Workplace","slug":"beyond-the-workplace","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":123096,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":3,"filter":"raw"},{"term_id":271,"name":"Commentary","slug":"commentary","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":111707,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":259,"filter":"raw"},{"term_id":33253,"name":"mentoring","slug":"mentoring","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":47172,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":61,"filter":"raw"},{"term_id":1038466,"name":"mentoring programs","slug":"mentoring-programs","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":116230,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":2,"filter":"raw"},{"term_id":304144,"name":"mentorship","slug":"mentorship","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":121881,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":3,"filter":"raw"},{"term_id":3812524,"name":"palantir","slug":"palantir","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":114157,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":6,"filter":"raw"},{"term_id":21887957,"name":"Roxane Gay","slug":"roxane-gay","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":123097,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":2,"filter":"raw"},{"term_id":115501,"name":"sexual harassment","slug":"sexual-harassment","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":112566,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":6,"filter":"raw"}],"has_commentary_tag":true,"primary_tag":{"name":"Commentary","slug":"commentary","url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/tag\/commentary\/"},"paid":false,"paid_excerpt":"The mentor\/mentee relationship is a professional one and should be treated as such. It really is that simple.","seo":{"seo_title":"When mentors cross the line","seo_description":"The mentor\/mentee relationship is a profe