evenue per customer is up 7.8% on the year, thanks to higher prices.<\/p>\n<p>So if your large soda and tub of buttery popcorn is putting you back even more than it used to, now you know why.<\/p>\n","time":{"pretty":"February 18, 2015","published":"2015-02-18 02:24:34","updated":"2015-02-18 02:24:34","minute":"2:24 PM EST","is_same_day":false,"is_home_pop":true},"comment_url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/18\/movie-theaters-concessions\/","absolute_url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/18\/movie-theaters-concessions\/","redirect_url":"","partner":"","outbrain_url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/18\/movie-theaters-concessions\/","outbrain_footer":true,"outbrain_right_rail":false,"short_title":"Movie theaters are selling few tickets, but making more on snacks","post_type":"post","featured_type":"image","featured_image":{"src":"https:\/\/fortunedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2015\/02\/145031081.jpg?quality=80&w=840&h=485&crop=1","class":"featured-img-article_full","credit":"Photograph by Frederic J. Brown \u2014 AFP\/Getty Images","caption":"","attach_id":"996272"},"excerpt":"<p>Have you noticed how expensive your popcorn&#8217;s getting?<\/p>\n","authors":[{"id":"276574","url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/author\/ben-geier\/","name":"Ben Geier","twitter":"ben_geier","gplus":"","email":"","thumbnail":"<img width=\"59\" height=\"59\" src=\"https:\/\/fortunedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/05\/ben-geier-6101.jpg?quality=80&amp;w=59\" class=\"avatar avatar-59 photo wp-post-image\" alt=\"WRITER HEADSHOTS \u2014 Ben Geier headshot\" \/>","thumbnail_alt":"","thumbnail_src":["https:\/\/fortunedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/05\/ben-geier-6101.jpg?quality=80&w=150",150,150,true],"bio":"Ben Geier is a writer at Fortune.com","title":"","company":"","is_contributor":"not-contributor"}],"sections":{"13879":{"term_id":13879,"name":"Retail","slug":"retail","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":46735,"taxonomy":"category","description":"News and updates on the retail sector, including companies like Wal-Mart, Target, Costco, Sears, Home Depot, and other places to shop.","parent":0,"count":1468,"object_id":996026,"filter":"raw"}},"section":{"name":"Retail","slug":"retail","url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/retail\/","newsletter_info":"The Fortune Daily"},"tags":{"190":{"term_id":190,"name":"Movies","slug":"movies","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":55291,"taxonomy":"post_tag","description":"","parent":0,"count":25,"object_id":996026,"filter":"raw"}},"has_commentary_tag":false,"primary_tag":{"name":"Movies","slug":"movies","url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/tag\/movies\/"},"paid":false,"paid_excerpt":"Have you noticed how expensive your popcorn&#8217;s getting?","seo":{"seo_title":"AMC Lost on Ticket Sales, But Made More From Concessions","seo_description":"Movie theaters are making up for falling ticket sales by hiking the cost of popcorn and other snacks.","seo_keywords":"movies, popcorn, concessions, amc","seo_news_keywords":"","seo_additional_meta":""},"social":{"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ffortune.com%2F2015%2F02%2F18%2Fmovie-theaters-concessions%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Ffor.tn%2F17r6grZ","encoded_title":"The+sneaky+way+movie+theaters+are+making+up+for+falling+ticket%C2%A0sales","twitter_text":"The sneaky way movie theaters are making up for falling ticket sales","twitter_via":"FORTUNE","facebook_desc":"Have you noticed how expensive your popcorn's getting?","facebook_title":"The Sneaky Way Movie Theaters Are Making Up For Falling Ticket Sales"},"format":{"term_id":2710,"name":"Article","slug":"fortune-post-format-article","term_group":0,"term_taxonomy_id":3,"taxonomy":"fortune_post_format","description":"","parent":0,"count":11096,"filter":"raw"},"related_posts":[]},{"id":997068,"content_type":"free full","is_magazine_content":"non-magazine","url":"\/2015\/02\/19\/snapchat-worth-19-billion-more\/","title":"Why Snapchat is worth $19 billion (or more)","content":"<p>An executive\u2014his\/her name isn&#8217;t important to this tale\u2014stopped by <em>Fortune<\/em>&#8216;s New York headquarters sometime last week. At one point during our conversation, Snapchat came up.<\/p>\n<p><em>&#8220;You see what Snapchat&#8217;s doing lately?&#8221;<\/em><\/p>\n<p><em>&#8220;No. I try to limit the number of messaging apps on my phone. Late adopter.&#8221;<\/em><\/p>\n<p><em>&#8220;What they&#8217;re doing is amazing. The new Discover feature? They&#8217;re so far past ephemeral messaging.&#8221;<\/em><\/p>\n<p>The enthusiasm was infectious. (And no, the executive didn&#8217;t work for the company in question.)<\/p>\n<p>On Wednesday news broke that Snapchat was reportedly <a href=\"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/18\/snapchat-seeking-a-19-billion-valuation-with-latest-round-of-funding\/\">raising a new round of funding<\/a> that would value the Los Angeles company at $19 billion. It&#8217;s an astounding figure if you think about it\u2014a few billion short of the current market value of Tesla Motors <span class=\"tickershortcode quotecard_hook unprocessed neutral\" data-symbol=\"TSLA\">\n\t\t\t\t<span class=\"wrapper trend-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"exit_trigger_set\" href=\"\/company\/tsla\/\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"ticker\">TSLA<\/span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"change percent\"><\/span>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/a>\n\t\t\t\t<\/span>\n\t\t\t<\/span>, Elon Musk&#8217;s groundbreaking electric car company, and ahead of Symantec <span class=\"tickershortcode quotecard_hook unprocessed neutral\" data-symbol=\"SYMC\">\n\t\t\t\t<span class=\"wrapper trend-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"exit_trigger_set\" href=\"\/company\/symc\/\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"ticker\">SYMC<\/span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"change percent\"><\/span>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/a>\n\t\t\t\t<\/span>\n\t\t\t<\/span>, by some estimates the world&#8217;s leading cyber security company. It would make Snapchat the third-most valuable tech startup that does not trade its shares publicly. (To see a comprehensive list of those companies, visit the <a href=\"http:\/\/fortune.com\/unicorns\/\"><em>Fortune<\/em> Unicorn List<\/a>.)<\/p>\n<p>When the news broke, the first question that usually arose was some form of the following: &#8220;Nineteen billion dollars for a disappearing-messaging app?&#8221; Translation: All this for a stupid mobile app that teenagers use as a back channel to goof off with their friends?<\/p>\n<p>In a word, yes.<\/p>\n<p>Snapchat, which launched in 2011, reportedly generates little revenue and has yet to turn a profit. But the broad strokes of its business model are well-worn: marshal a captivated audience, sell advertisements against it, profit.<\/p>\n<p>The latest reports put Snapchat&#8217;s user base at more than 100 million people, though the exact number has not been publicly disclosed and could be well beyond that. Compare that to LinkedIn&#8217;s roughly 200 million (<a href=\"http:\/\/fortune.com\/company\/lnkd\/\">LNKD<\/a> market cap: about $33 billion), Twitter&#8217;s almost 300 million (<a href=\"http:\/\/fortune.com\/company\/twtr\/\">TWTR<\/a>: about $30 billion), and Facebook&#8217;s 1.4 billion (<a href=\"http:\/\/fortune.com\/company\/fb\/\">FB<\/a>: $212 billion) and the math\u2014preposterous as it seems\u2014starts to make sense.<\/p>\n<p>(It also shows how aggressive Facebook has been in preserving its lead: It paid $19 billion for WhatsApp, which has about 700 million users, and $1 billion for Instagram, which now has more than 300 million.)<\/p>\n<p>Snapchat CEO Evan Spiegel has already indicated that his company is beginning to get serious about revenue; <a href=\"http:\/\/blogs.wsj.com\/digits\/2014\/10\/09\/snapchat-ceo-spiegel-says-untargeted-advertising-is-coming-soon\/\">he said as much<\/a> at an industry conference in October. If the company can demonstrate that it can figure out a way to make money at least as well as its peers\u2014never mind the fact that its customers are almost entirely within the age 18-34 demographic that advertisers have traditionally most coveted\u2014$19 billion isn&#8217;t a goal; it&#8217;s practically a done deal.<\/p>\n<p><em>More about Snapchat on Fortune.com:<\/em><\/p>\n<p><em>My colleague <a href=\"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/18\/i-was-right-and-wrong-about-snapchat\/\">Dan Primack looks back on his thoughts<\/a>, right and wrong, about CEO Spiegel.<\/em><\/p>\n<p><em>These messaging apps are worth a lot if they&#8217;ve <a href=\"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/01\/28\/swyft-messaging-emoji\/\">already spawned an economy around them<\/a>, my colleague Erin Griffith writes.<\/em><\/p>\n<p><em>Plus, we kinda told you so. <a href=\"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2013\/12\/18\/countdown-to-the-snapchat-revolution\/\">Read our Snapchat feature story<\/a> in the December 18, 2013 issue of Fortune magazine.<\/em><\/p>\n","time":{"pretty":"February 19, 2015","published":"2015-02-19 08:39:02","updated":"2015-02-19 08:39:02","minute":"8:39 AM EST","is_same_day":true,"is_home_pop":true},"comment_url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/19\/snapchat-worth-19-billion-more\/","absolute_url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/19\/snapchat-worth-19-billion-more\/","redirect_url":"","partner":"","outbrain_url":"http:\/\/fortune.com\/2015\/02\/19\/snapchat-worth-19-billion-more\/","outbrain_footer":true,"outbrain_right_rail":true,"short_title":"Yes, Snapchat is worth $19 billion (or more)","post_type":"post","featured_type":"video","featured_video":{"html":"<div class=\"video-wrapper\"  data-ratio=\"1\" data-pos=\"35\">\n\t\t\t\t<object id=\"bc-video-3969071998001-35\" class=\"BrightcoveExperience\"><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#FFFFFF\"\/><param name=\"width\" value=\"100%\"\/><param name=\"height\" value=\"100%\"\/><param name=\"playerID\" value=\"3160175193001\"\/><param name=\"playerKey\" value=\"AQ~~,AAAB668kGak~,LMlvL4u4ShOTHD9z00VquajMOcH97tcW\"\/><param name=\"isVid\" value=\"true\"\/><param name=\"isUI\" value=\"true\"\/><param name=\"videoSmoothing\" value=\"true\"\/><param name=\"seamlessTabbing\" value=\"fals